# Wath agent — process flow operating procedure

Execute the onboarding as ordered stages. **Do not skip ahead.** Each stage has a definition of
done (DoD); if you cannot meet it, stop and report rather than proceeding.

This flow applies to **first onboarding and every re-run** — the user may update
`INTEGRATION_REQUIREMENTS.md` (new runtime, new constraints, validation feedback) and submit
again; your job is always to integrate against the **current** requirements and repo state.

The **governing standard** is named in the onboarding prompt (SKILL.md under `standards/`).
All artifact paths, rules, and anti-patterns come from that standard — not from this file.

## Stage 1 — Detect
Read the repo and `INTEGRATION_REQUIREMENTS.md`. Determine: runtime (kubernetes/nomad/vm), stack,
target environments, identity (namespaces / service accounts / claims), and any anti-patterns
the standard flags (e.g. static credentials, missing egress rules).

Derive the **auth method from runtime** per the standard's auth table — do not hardcode kubernetes
when requirements say nomad or vm.

**DoD:** runtime and intent unambiguous; anti-patterns identified. Missing/contradictory required
fields → ask the submitter; do not assume.

## Stage 2 — Compose / select standard
Load the governing standard SKILL. Honor the what-vs-admin boundary (consumer vs platform admin).
State the upgrade rationale explicitly (e.g. tier-1→tier-4, or baseline→compliant).

**DoD:** you can name every conformance rule you must satisfy, the auth method you'll use, and
the target compliance posture.

## Stage 3 — Parameterize (typed params first)
Emit `integration.params.json` conforming to the standard's schema. This is the source of truth
for TTLs, capabilities, identity binding, and delivery **before** any rendered config.

**DoD:** params validate against the schema. If a value would violate a bound, fix intent — do
not widen the bound.

## Stage 4 — Render artifacts
From the params, generate every artifact listed in the standard's artifact layout (SKILL §2) and
the onboarding prompt checklist. Render from params — do not free-write policy/config.

**DoD:** all artifacts present; admin prerequisites captured as a PR checklist, not executed.

## Stage 5 — Verify in sandbox
Run the standard's conformance gate (`conformance/verify.sh`). If behavioral verification is
available for this standard, prove the identity → authorization → secret-delivery flow in the
sandbox.

**DoD:** the gate passes. **A failing gate is a hard stop** — fix artifacts and re-verify; never
weaken a check or the standard to make it pass.

## Stage 6 — Open PR
Open one PR (`autoCreatePR`) against the application repository. The PR description **MUST**
follow `.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE/wath-onboarding.md` (or the standard's configured template)
— complete every section: rationale, artifact checkboxes, verification evidence, admin
prerequisites, SME assumptions.

Include the PR template file in the branch if not already present (Wath materializes it under
`.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE/`).

**DoD:** PR is reviewable against evidence, not vibes. Then stop — review and merge are human.

---
**If at any stage the standard is silent or the case is novel/ambiguous, halt and escalate to a
human SME.** Forward progress is never worth inventing an unratified pattern.
